    "### Preprocessing"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The preprocessing of the images understand some modifications to make on the photos to use them as input to the model. Some of them depend on that applied to the images on which the ViT model was pre-trained. We will demystify the major transformations made on the ImageNet to be fed inside the ViT Model. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Normalization"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Like we did to calculate the means and variance of the images, we can at first **divide the images' arrays by 255** to process float values. Doing so also made the means and the variances scaled between 0 and 1. Dividing the images by the maximum pixel prevents the model from exploding gradient while being trained. The gradient exploding make the weights tend to infinity and not to converge anymore because, with the stochastic gradient descent, we have the following computation, which is made at each new update of the weights: $w = w - \\delta_w \\times \\alpha$, where $w$ represent a weight matrix, $\\delta_w$ is the derivation of the loss compared with the weight matrix and $\\alpha$ is the step size. If $\\delta_w \\sim \\infty$ then $w$ also tends to $\\infty$. \n",
    "\n",
    "![exploding_gradient](sdsaldjksld.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "The second normalization we can do is for the transfer learning task and imply normalizing the image by the same mean and standard deviation as the transferred model was pre-trained on. It will add stability to the fine-tuning because the pictures will have the same distribution as the base images and then totally simplify the adaptation of the model to the new photos. The following illustration may make you better understand.\n",
    "\n",
    "![transferring_ability](https://i0.wp.com/datascientest.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/illu_DLtransfer_blog-33.png?resize=1024%2C562&ssl=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The pre-trained ViT Model implies taking the value of $0.5$ for both the means and the standard deviations at each color. We must then take the same values when normalizing the new images. The normalization is done by making the following transformation on each pixel:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "pix^{\\prime} = \\frac{pix - pix \\times 0.5}{pix \\times 0.5} \n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$pix^{\\prime}$ represents the normalized pixel and $pix$, the original one."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Resizing and resampling strategies"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The different images must have the same size but only. Our current images (images of faces) are all of the same size, which is $$height = 600 \\space pixels, width = 600 \\space pixels, channels = 3$$. However, for the transfer learning, we must make the images the same size as the original ones. The ViT Model was trained on images of $size = (224, 224)$ without considering the number of channels. It is done because the linear projection using the ViT Model takes as enter a sequence of inputs where each of them initially has the following height and width $224 / \\sqrt{256} = 14$. The value of $256$ is the number of patches we send to the model as a sequence. Each patch will contain $16\\times 16$ pixels for each channel. Let us explain it by creating $256$ patches from our current images:\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose we want to get patches from the following random image in our dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<PIL.JpegImagePlugin.JpegImageFile image mode=RGB size=600x600>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 22,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "random.seed(89)\n",
    "\n",
    "image = Image.open(random.choice(glob('data/real_and_fake_face/training_real/*')))\n",
    "\n",
    "image"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We must know how many pixels are horizontally and vertically inside the image, which is the height and width of the picture."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "height, width = image.size # will return 600 for height and 600 for width"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Knowing that we will need 256 patches (part of the images), we will need to identify the height and width of each patch by dividing them by the square root of the number of patches. The result is a decimal, so let us take only the integer part. We will lose some pixels but only for the explanation. We will explain how to solve this problem later when resampling and when describing the method used by the ViT Model to project the patches (in this notebook [vit_model](vit_model.ipynb))."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Height and width of each patch: (37, 37)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# let us calculate the number of divisions to make to the width and height of the image\n",
    "n_patch = int(sqrt(256)) \n",
    "\n",
    "patch_h = int(height / n_patch) # notice that the height must be divisible by the number of divisions\n",
    "\n",
    "patch_w = int(width / n_patch) # notice that the width must be divisible by the number of divisions\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Height and width of each patch: {(patch_h, patch_w)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then each patch must have a **(37, 37)** size. To recuperate the patches with the precise size, we must define **16 boxes with their coordinates** according to the height's axis and the width's axis of the image. The position of a box is defined by taking the coordinate of the top left of the box and that of the bottom right of the box. The first box will have coordinates of -> **(top_left = (0, 0), bottom_right = (37, 37))**. We only need to identify the first coordinate and add the patch size to find the second coordinate. For the next boxes, we must modify the top_left by adding patch size at each time to one of the height's axes (the first number of the coordinate) and width axes (the second number of the coordinate) of a current box 'a number of divisions' times. We identify the second coordinate each time to trace the whole box. Let us trace the first (in <i style = \"color: red\">red</i>) and the second (in <i style = \"color: cyan\">cyan</i>) coordinates of the boxes inside a figure. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Note**: The `product` creates a tuple for each possible coordinate between position on the height's axis going from 0 to $patch\\_h \\times n\\_patch$ by step of $patch\\_h$ and position on width's axis going from 0 to $path\\_w \\times n\\_patch$ by step of $patch\\_w$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1400x800 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# we will find the first coordinates of the boxes with product function of itertools\n",
    "first_coordinates = list(itertools.product(range(0, patch_h * n_patch, patch_h),\n",
    "                                      range(0, patch_w * n_patch, patch_w)))\n",
    "\n",
    "# get the first coordinates of the boxes\n",
    "poses_h = [c[0] for c in first_coordinates]\n",
    "poses_w = [c[1] for c in first_coordinates]\n",
    "\n",
    "# get the second coordinates of the boxes by adding to the first coordinates the patch height and width\n",
    "poses_h_2 = [c[0] + patch_h for c in first_coordinates]\n",
    "poses_w_2 = [c[1] + patch_w for c in first_coordinates]\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, sharey=True, sharex=True, figsize = (14, 8))\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].scatter(poses_w, poses_h, label = 'first_coordinates', color = 'red')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel('height')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel('width')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].set_title(\"Firt coordinates\")\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].invert_yaxis()\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].grid()\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].scatter(poses_w_2, poses_h_2, label = 'second_coordinates', color = 'blue')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].set_title(\"Second coordinates\")\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel('height')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel('width')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].invert_yaxis()\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].grid()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The coordinates are placed on the images like in the above figure. Notice the y-axis is inverted compared to the height axis of the picture."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us create a function that identifies the patches of the image according to the positions of the boxes with the `crop` function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Overwriting fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/utils/get_patches.py\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%writefile fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/utils/get_patches.py\n",
    "\n",
    "from PIL.JpegImagePlugin import JpegImageFile\n",
    "from math import *\n",
    "import itertools\n",
    "\n",
    "def get_patches(image: JpegImageFile, n_patches: int):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # get height and width of the image\n",
    "    height, width = image.size \n",
    "    \n",
    "    # let us calculate the number of divisions to make to the width and height of the image\n",
    "    n_patch = int(sqrt(n_patches)) \n",
    "\n",
    "    patch_h = int(height / n_patch) # notice that the height must be divisible by the number of divisions\n",
    "\n",
    "    patch_w = int(width / n_patch) # notice that the width must be divisible by the number of divisions\n",
    "\n",
    "    print(f\"Height and width of each patch: {(patch_h, patch_w)}\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # we will find the first coordinates of the boxes with product function of itertools\n",
    "    first_coordinates = list(itertools.product(range(0, patch_h * n_patch, patch_h),\n",
    "                                        range(0, patch_w * n_patch, patch_w)))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    patches = []\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for pos1, pos2 in first_coordinates:\n",
    "        \n",
    "        box = (pos2, pos1, pos2 + patch_w, pos1 + patch_h)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        patches.append(image.crop(box))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return patches\n",
    "    \n",
    "    \n",
    "    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us recuperate the patches."
   ]
  },

   "execution_count": 27,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Height and width of each patch: (37, 37)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%run fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/utils/get_patches.py\n",
    "\n",
    "patches = get_patches(image, 256)"
   ]
  },

    "We obtain the following patches."

   "source": [
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_patch, n_patch, figsize = (18, 18))\n",
    "\n",
    "fig.patch.set_facecolor('white')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes = axes.flat\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(len(patches)):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    axes[i].imshow(patches[i])\n",
    "    \n",
    "    axes[i].set_title(f'Patch {i+1}')\n",
    "    \n",
    "    axes[i].axis('off')\n",
    "    \n",
    "fig.tight_layout()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The size of a patch is $(37, 37)$; however, knowing that the ViT Model accepts only patches of size $(14, 14)$. Then our images must be resized to match that of the original images. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "----------------"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To resize the images, we can use the `box filter` to down-scale them. The box filter calculates the average values inside a box (the same boxes we defined earlier). To obtain that result, we can modify the function we created to get the patches and use `numpy` to calculate the mean of the pixels. We do that because the size of the images is greater than that of the base images of the ViT Model's pre-training. But if the size of our photos were smaller, we would use more sophisticated methods to resample the images like **the cubic**, **the nearest neighbor**, **the bilinear** interpolations, or the up-scaler **box** method. We will explain them in another notebook. For now, let us create a function that takes an image and down-scale it to the correct size.  \n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Notice that dividing the height of our images by the height of the original image and doing so for the widths will give us the following value $600 / 224 = 2.67$. That value represents the boxes' height and width in order to downscale the images. But it is impossible to use it since it is a decimal number. To solve the issue, we will take the boxes' height and width to be round of the value found, equal to $3$. Then using that boxes, we will obtain a height and width of $600 / 3 = 200$ for the rescaled images, which is not equal to $224$. Then, we must add paddings to the bottom and right sides of the pictures to obtain the correct size. The number of pixels to add at each side equals $(224 - 200) * 3 = 72$. \n",
    "\n",
    "For the study, let us create a black image with a height and a width of $600 + 72 = 672$ and add it to the image we want to rescale. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Remark**: There are better methods than adding paddings to the images to obtain the correct size. Another technique is used in the pre-implemented feature extraction pipeline available in HugginFace."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 29,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<PIL.Image.Image image mode=RGB size=672x672>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 29,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# let us create an empty image\n",
    "pad_image = Image.new('RGB', size=(672, 672), color='black')\n",
    "\n",
    "# place the previous image inside it\n",
    "pad_image.paste(image)\n",
    "\n",
    "# we obtain \n",
    "pad_image"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now let us modify the previous function to rescale the image with the methods that we defined earlier."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Overwriting fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/utils/downscale_image.py\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%writefile fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/utils/downscale_image.py\n",
    "\n",
    "from PIL.JpegImagePlugin import JpegImageFile\n",
    "from PIL import Image\n",
    "from math import *\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import itertools\n",
    "\n",
    "def downscale_image(image: JpegImageFile, size: tuple = (224, 224)):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    assert image.size[0] % size[0] == 0 and image.size[1] % size[1] == 0\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # get box size\n",
    "    height, width = int(image.size[0] / size[0]), int(image.size[1] / size[1]) \n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(f\"Height and width of each box: {(height, width)}\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # we will concatenate the patches over the height axis (axis 0)\n",
    "    patches = []\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for j in range(0, size[1] * width, width):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # we must recuperate each width division in order to concatenate the results (on axis 1)\n",
    "        h_div = []\n",
    "        \n",
    "        for i in range(0, size[0] * height, height):\n",
    "        \n",
    "            box = (j, i, j + width, i + height)\n",
    "            \n",
    "            current_box = image.crop(box)\n",
    "            \n",
    "            # let us convert the box to a numpy array and calculate the mean\n",
    "            current_box = np.array(current_box).mean(axis = (0, 1))[np.newaxis, np.newaxis, :]\n",
    "            \n",
    "            # add to h_div\n",
    "            h_div.append(current_box)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # concatenate over width axis\n",
    "        patches.append(np.concatenate(h_div, axis = 0))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # concatenate over the height axis and transform to a pillow image\n",
    "    image = Image.fromarray(np.uint8(np.concatenate(patches, axis = 1)))   \n",
    "    \n",
    "    return image\n",
    "    \n",
    "    \n",
    "    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us downscale the image."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Height and width of each box: (3, 3)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%run fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/utils/downscale_image.py\n",
    "\n",
    "dscale_image = downscale_image(pad_image)"
   ]
  },

    "------------"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Custom dataset"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The custom dataset will recuperate as arguments the path of the images, the label weights, and a transformer. It has the following signature:\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "\n",
    "class FakeFaceDetectionDataset(Dataset):\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __init__(self, path: str, weights: list, transformer):\n",
    "\n",
    "        pass\n",
    "\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 33,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from PIL import Image"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 34,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "<PIL.JpegImagePlugin.JpegImageFile image mode=RGB size=600x600 at 0x225420D4E80>\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "with Image.open('data/real_and_fake_face/training_fake/easy_100_1111.jpg') as img:\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(img)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 35,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Overwriting fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/data/fake_face_dataset.py\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%writefile fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/data/fake_face_dataset.py\n",
    "\n",
    "from fake_face_detection.utils.compute_weights import compute_weights\n",
    "from torch.utils.data import Dataset\n",
    "from PIL import Image\n",
    "from glob import glob\n",
    "import torch\n",
    "import os\n",
    "\n",
    "class FakeFaceDetectionDataset(Dataset):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def __init__(self, fake_path: str, real_path: str, id_map: dict, transformer, **transformer_kwargs):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # let us load the images \n",
    "        self.fake_images = glob(os.path.join(fake_path, \"*\"))\n",
    "        \n",
    "        self.real_images = glob(os.path.join(real_path, \"*\"))\n",
    "        \n",
    "        self.images = self.fake_images + self.real_images\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # let us recuperate the labels\n",
    "        self.fake_labels = [int(id_map['fake'])] * len(self.fake_images)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        self.real_labels = [int(id_map['real'])] * len(self.real_images)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        self.labels = self.fake_labels + self.real_labels\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # let us recuperate the weights\n",
    "        self.weights = torch.from_numpy(compute_weights(self.labels))\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # let us recuperate the transformer\n",
    "        self.transformer = transformer\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # let us recuperate the length\n",
    "        self.length = len(self.labels)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # let us recuperate the transformer kwargs\n",
    "        self.transformer_kwargs = transformer_kwargs\n",
    "        \n",
    "    def __getitem__(self, index):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # let us recuperate an image\n",
    "        image = self.images[index]\n",
    "        \n",
    "        with Image.open(image) as img:\n",
    "        \n",
    "            # let us recuperate a label\n",
    "            label = self.labels[index]\n",
    "            \n",
    "            # let us add a transformation on the images\n",
    "            if self.transformer:\n",
    "                \n",
    "                image = self.transformer(img, **self.transformer_kwargs)\n",
    "                \n",
    "        # let us add the label inside the obtained dictionary\n",
    "        image['labels'] = label\n",
    "        \n",
    "        return image    \n",
    "        \n",
    "    def __len__(self):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        return self.length\n",
    "        "
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us initialize the dataset and load some data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from fake_face_detection.data.fake_face_dataset import FakeFaceDetectionDataset\n",
    "from fake_face_detection.utils.compute_weights import compute_weights"
   ]
  },

    "We can see that it uses the following preprocessing steps:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Resizing the images to **(224, 224, 3)** with the **Box** Resampling Strategy.\n",
    "- Multiplying the images by a rescale factor of $0.00392156862745098 = \\frac{1}{255}$ to normalize them.\n",
    "- Standardize the images using the means of $0.5$ and a standard deviation of $0.5$ for each color."

    "                                       id_map = characs['ids'], transformer=feature_extractor, transformer_kwargs={'return_tensors': 'pt'})"

  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us implement the data collator function below. It will be passed as a parameter to ViT Trainer."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Overwriting fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/data/collator.py\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%writefile fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/data/collator.py\n",
    "\n",
    "import torch\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "def fake_face_collator(batch): \n",
    "    \"\"\"The data collator for training vision transformer models on fake and real face dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        batch (list): A dictionary containing the pixel values and the labels\n",
    "\n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        dict: The final dictionary\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    \n",
    "    new_batch = {\n",
    "        'pixel_values': [],\n",
    "        'labels': []\n",
    "    }\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for x in batch:\n",
    "        \n",
    "        pixel_values = torch.from_numpy(x['pixel_values'][0]) if isinstance(x['pixel_values'][0], np.ndarray) \\\n",
    "            else x['pixel_values'][0]\n",
    "        \n",
    "        new_batch['pixel_values'].append(pixel_values)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        new_batch['labels'].append(torch.tensor(x['labels']))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    new_batch['pixel_values'] = torch.stack(new_batch['pixel_values'])\n",
    "    \n",
    "    new_batch['labels'] = torch.stack(new_batch['labels'])\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return new_batch"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Loss function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We must create a function that returns a custom trainer after attributing weight to the loss function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Overwriting fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/trainers/custom_trainer.py\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "%%writefile fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/trainers/custom_trainer.py\n",
    "\n",
    "from transformers import Trainer\n",
    "import torch\n",
    "\n",
    "def get_custom_trainer(weights: torch.Tensor): \n",
    "    \n",
    "    class CustomTrainer(Trainer): # got from https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/main_classes/trainer\n",
    "        \n",
    "        def compute_loss(self, model, inputs, return_outputs=False):\n",
    "            \n",
    "            # recuperate labels\n",
    "            labels = inputs.get(\"labels\")\n",
    "            \n",
    "            # forward pass\n",
    "            outputs = model(**inputs)\n",
    "\n",
    "            # recuperate logits\n",
    "            logits = outputs.get(\"logits\")\n",
    "            \n",
    "            # compute custom loss (passing the weights)\n",
    "            loss_fct = nn.CrossEntropyLoss(weight=weights)\n",
    "            \n",
    "            loss = loss_fct(logits.view(-1, self.model.config.num_labels), labels.view(-1))\n",
    "            \n",
    "            return (loss, outputs) if return_outputs else loss\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return CustomTrainer"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%run fake-face-detection/fake_face_detection/trainers/custom_trainer.py"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   ]
